/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰# Loc strings for various entity state & client-side PVS related commands
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-reset-ent-help = Usage: resetent <Entity UID>
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-reset-ent-desc = Reset an entity to the most recently received server state. This will also reset entities that have been detached to null-space.
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-reset-all-ents-help = Usage: resetallents
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-reset-all-ents-desc = Resets all entities to the most recently received server state. This only impacts entities that have not been detached to null-space.
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-detach-ent-help = Usage: detachent <Entity UID>
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-detach-ent-desc = Detach an entity to null-space, as if it had left PVS range.
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-local-delete-help = Usage: localdelete <Entity UID>
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-local-delete-desc = Deletes an entity. Unlike the normal delete command, this is CLIENT-SIDE. Unless the entity is a client-side entity, this will likely cause errors.
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-full-state-reset-help = Usage: fullstatereset
/Locale/en-US/client-state-commands.ftl鎰cmd-full-state-reset-desc = Discards any entity state information and requests a full-state from the server.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰### Localization for engine console commands
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-hint-float = [float]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## generic command errors
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-invalid-arg-number-error = Invalid number of arguments.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-integer = {$arg} is not a valid integer.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-float = {$arg} is not a valid float.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-bool = {$arg} is not a valid bool.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-uid = {$arg} is not a valid entity UID.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-mapid = {$arg} is not a valid MapId.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-enum = {$arg} is not a {$enum} Enum.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-grid = {$arg} is not a valid grid.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-cultureinfo = "{$arg}" is not valid CultureInfo.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-entity-exist = UID {$arg} does not correspond to an existing entity.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-parse-failure-session = There is no session with username: {$username}
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-error-file-not-found = Could not find file: {$file}.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-error-dir-not-found = Could not find directory: {$dir}.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-failure-no-attached-entity = There is no entity attached to this shell.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'help' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-desc = Display general help or help text for a specific command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-help = Usage: help [command name]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    When no command name is provided, displays general-purpose help text. If a command name is provided, displays help text for that command.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-no-args = To display help for a specific command, write 'help <command>'. To list all available commands, write 'list'. To search for commands, use 'list <filter>'.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-unknown = Unknown command: { $command }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-top = { $command } - { $description }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-invalid-args = Invalid amount of arguments.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-help-arg-cmdname = [command name]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'cvar' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-desc = Gets or sets a CVar.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-help = Usage: cvar <name | ?> [value]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    If a value is passed, the value is parsed and stored as the new value of the CVar.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    If not, the current value of the CVar is displayed.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Use 'cvar ?' to get a list of all registered CVars.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-invalid-args = Must provide exactly one or two arguments.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-not-registered = CVar '{ $cvar }' is not registered. Use 'cvar ?' to get a list of all registered CVars.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-parse-error = Input value is in incorrect format for type { $type }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-compl-list = List available CVars
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-arg-name = <name | ?>
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar-value-hidden = <value hidden>
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'cvar_subs' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar_subs-desc = Lists the OnValueChanged subscriptions for a CVar.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar_subs-help = Usage: cvar_subs <name>
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar_subs-invalid-args = Must provide exactly one argument.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-cvar_subs-arg-name = <name>
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'list' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-list-desc = Lists available commands, with optional search filter
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-list-help = Usage: list [filter]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Lists all available commands. If an argument is provided, it will be used to filter commands by name.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-list-heading = SIDE NAME            DESC{"\u000A"}-------------------------{"\u000A"}
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-list-arg-filter = [filter]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## '>' command, aka remote exec
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-remoteexec-desc = Executes server-side commands
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-remoteexec-help = Usage: > <command> [arg] [arg] [arg...]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Executes a command on the server. This is necessary if a command with the same name exists on the client, as simply running the command would run the client command first.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'gc' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc-desc = Run the GC (Garbage Collector)
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc-help = Usage: gc [generation]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Uses GC.Collect() to execute the Garbage Collector.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    If an argument is provided, it is parsed as a GC generation number and GC.Collect(int) is used.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Use the 'gfc' command to do an LOH-compacting full GC.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc-failed-parse = Failed to parse argument.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc-arg-generation = [generation]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'gcf' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gcf-desc = Run the GC, fully, compacting LOH and everything.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gcf-help = Usage: gcf
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    Does a full GC.Collect(2, GCCollectionMode.Forced, true, true) while also compacting LOH.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    This will probably lock up for hundreds of milliseconds, be warned.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰## 'gc_mode' command
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-desc = Change/Read the GC Latency mode
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-help = Usage: gc_mode [type]
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    If no argument is provided, returns the current GC latency mode.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰    If an argument is passed, it is parsed as GCLatencyMode and set as the GC latency mode.
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-current = current gc latency mode: { $prevMode }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-possible = possible modes:
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-option = - { $mode }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-unknown = unknown gc latency mode: { $arg }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-attempt = attempting gc latency mode change: { $prevMode } -> { $mode }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-result = resulting gc latency mode: { $mode }
/Locale/en-US/commands.ftl鎰cmd-gc_mode-arg-type = [type]

/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰# Used internally by the THE() function.
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰zzzz-the = { PROPER($ent) ->
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰    *[false] the { $ent }
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰     [true] { $ent }
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰    }
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰# Used internally by the SUBJECT() function.

/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰    [male] he
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰    [female] she
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰    [epicene] they
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰   *[neuter] it
/Locale/en-US/_engine_lib.ftl鎰   }

/Locale/en-US/tips.ftl鎰tips-dataset-38 = As a Traitor, plasma gas is an excellent way to create chaos. It can be ignited to make an area extra-uninhabitable, and can cause toxin damage to those that inhale it.

/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰# Used internally by the POWERJOULES() function.
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰# Reminder: 1 joule = 1 watt for 1 second (multiply watts by seconds to get joules).
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰# Therefore 1 kilowatt-hour is equal to 3,600,000 joules (3.6MJ)
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰zzzz-fmt-power-joules = { TOSTRING($divided, "F1") } { $places ->
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    [0] J
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    [1] kJ
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    [2] MJ
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    [3] GJ
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    [4] TJ
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰    *[5] ???
/Locale/en-US/_lib.ftl鎰}

/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰### Interaction Messages
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character climbs on $climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-user-climbs = You jump onto { THE($climbable) }!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to others when $user climbs on $climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-user-climbs-other  = { CAPITALIZE(THE($user)) } jumps onto { THE($climbable) }!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character forces someone to climb on $climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-user-climbs-force = You force { THE($moved-user) } onto { THE($climbable) }!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to others when someone forces other $moved-user to climb on $climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-user-climbs-force-other = { CAPITALIZE(THE($user)) } forces { THE($moved-user) } onto { THE($climbable) }!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character is far away from climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-cant-reach = You can't reach there!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character can't interact with climbable for some reason
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-cant-interact = You can't do that!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character isn't able to climb by their own actions
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-cant-climb = You are incapable of climbing!
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰# Shown to you when your character tries to force someone else who can't climb onto a climbable
/Locale/en-US/climbing/climbable-component.ftl鎰comp-climbable-target-cant-climb = { CAPITALIZE(THE($moved-user)) } can't go there!

/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰## PointingSystem
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-try-point-cannot-reach = You can't reach there!
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-self = You point at yourself.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-other = You point at {THE($other)}.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-self-others = {CAPITALIZE(THE($otherName))} points at {REFLEXIVE($other)}.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-other-others = {CAPITALIZE(THE($otherName))} points at {THE($other)}.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-you-other = {CAPITALIZE(THE($otherName))} points at you.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-at-tile = You point at the {$tileName}.
/Locale/en-US/entity-systems/pointing/pointing-system.ftl鎰pointing-system-point-in-own-inventory-self = You point at your {$item}.

/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰### Voting system related console commands
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰## 'createvote' command
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-createvote-desc = Creates a vote
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-createvote-help = Usage: createvote <'restart'|'preset'|'map'>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-createvote-cannot-call-vote-now = You can't call a vote right now!
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-createvote-invalid-vote-type = Invalid vote type
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-createvote-arg-vote-type = <vote type>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰## 'customvote' command
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-desc = Creates a custom vote
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-help = Usage: customvote <title> <option1> <option2> [option3...]
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-on-finished-tie = Tie between {$ties}!
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-on-finished-win = {$winner} wins!
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-arg-title = <title>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-customvote-arg-option-n = <option{ $n }>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰## 'vote' command
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-desc = Votes on an active vote
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-help = vote <voteId> <option>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-cannot-call-vote-now = You can't call a vote right now!
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-on-execute-error-must-be-player = Must be a player
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-on-execute-error-invalid-vote-id = Invalid vote ID
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-on-execute-error-invalid-vote-options = Invalid vote options
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-on-execute-error-invalid-vote = Invalid vote
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-vote-on-execute-error-invalid-option = Invalid option
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰## 'listvotes' command
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-listvotes-desc = Lists currently active votes
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-listvotes-help = Usage: listvotes
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰## 'cancelvote' command
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-cancelvote-desc = Cancels an active vote
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-cancelvote-help = Usage: cancelvote <id>
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰                      You can get the ID from the listvotes command.
/Locale/en-US/voting/vote-commands.ftl鎰cmd-cancelvote-error-invalid-vote-id = Invalid vote ID

/Locale/en-US/actions/actions/sleep.ftl鎰action-name-wake = Wake up
/Locale/en-US/actions/actions/sleep.ftl鎰sleep-onomatopoeia = Zzz...
/Locale/en-US/actions/actions/sleep.ftl鎰sleep-examined = [color=lightblue]{CAPITALIZE(SUBJECT($target))} {CONJUGATE-BE($target)} asleep.[/color]
/Locale/en-US/actions/actions/sleep.ftl鎰wake-other-success = You shake {THE($target)} awake.
/Locale/en-US/actions/actions/sleep.ftl鎰wake-other-failure = You shake {THE($target)}, but {SUBJECT($target)} {CONJUGATE-BE($target)} not waking up.

/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰## Messages shown to Pacified players when they try to do violence:
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰# With projectiles:
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-throw = I can't bring myself to throw { THE($projectile) }, that could hurt someone!
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰# With embedding projectiles:
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-throw-embed = No way I could throw { THE($projectile) }, that could get lodged inside someone!
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰# With liquid-spilling projectiles:
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-throw-spill = I can't possibly throw { THE($projectile) }, that could spill nasty stuff on someone!
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-harm-directly = I can't bring myself to hurt { THE($entity) }!
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-harm-indirect = I can't damage { THE($entity) }, it could hurt someone!
/Locale/en-US/pacified/pacified.ftl鎰pacified-cannot-fire-gun = I can't fire { THE($entity) }, it could hurt someone!

/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰book-text-atmos-distro = The distribution network, or "distro" for short, is the station's lifeline. It's responsible for transporting air from atmospherics throughout the station.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        Relevant pipes are often painted Popping Subdued Blue, but a surefire way to identify them is to use a tray scanner to trace which pipes are connected to active vents on the station.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        The standard gas mix of the distribution network is 20 degrees celsius, 78% nitrogen, 22% oxygen. You can check this by using a gas analyzer on a distro pipe or any vent connected to it. Special circumstances may call for special mixes.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        When it comes to deciding on a distro pressure, there are a few things to consider. Active vents will regulate the station's pressure, so as long as everything is functioning properly, there's no such thing as too high of a distro pressure.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        A higher distro pressure will allow the distro network to act as a buffer between the gas miners and vents, providing a significant amount of extra air that can be used to re-pressurize the station after a spacing.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        A lower distro pressure will reduce the amount of gas lost in the event that the distro is spaced, a quick way to deal with distro contamination. It can also help slow or prevent over-pressurization of the station in the event of vent issues.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        Common distro pressures are in the range of 300-375 kPa, but other pressures can be used with knowledge of the risks and benefits.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        The pressure of the network is determined by the last pump pumping into it. To prevent bottlenecks, all other pumps between the miners and the last pump should be set to their maximum rate, and any unnecessary devices should be removed.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        You can validate the distro pressure with a gas analyzer, but keep in mind that high demand due to things like spacings can cause the distro to be below the set target pressure for extended periods. So, if you see a dip in pressure, don't panic - it might be temporary.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰book-text-atmos-waste = The waste network is the primary system responsible for keeping the air on the station free of contaminants.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        You can identify the relevant pipes by their Pleasing Dull Red color or by using a tray scanner to trace which pipes are connected to the scrubbers on the station.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        The waste network is used to transport waste gasses to either be filtered or spaced. It is ideal to keep the pressure at 0 kPa, but it may sometimes be at a low non-zero pressure while in use.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        Technicians have the option to filter or space the waste gasses. While spacing is faster, filtering allows for the gasses to be reused for recycling or selling.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰        The waste network can also be used to diagnose atmospheric issues on the station. High levels of a waste gas may suggest a large leak, while the presence of non-waste gases may indicate a scrubber configuration or physical connection issue. If the gases are at a high temperature, it could indicate a fire.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰book-text-atmos-alarms = Air alarms are located throughout stations to allow management and monitoring of the local atmosphere.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            The air alarm interface provides technicians with a list of connected sensors, their readings, and the ability to adjust thresholds. These thresholds are used to determine the alarm condition of the air alarm. Technicians can also use the interface to set target pressures for vents and configure the operating speeds and targeted gases for scrubbers.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            While the interface allows for fine-tuning of the devices under the air alarm's control, there are also several modes available for rapid configuration of the alarm. These modes are automatically switched to when the alarm state changes:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            - Filtering: The default mode
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            - Filtering (wide): A filtering mode that modifies the operation of scrubbers to scrub a wider area
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            - Fill: Disables scrubbers and sets vents to their maximum pressure
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            - Panic: Disables vents and sets scrubbers to siphon
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰            A multitool or network configurator can be used to link devices to air alarms.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰book-text-atmos-vents =
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰    Below is a quick reference guide to several atmospheric devices:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                Passive Vents:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                These vents don't require power, they allow gases to flow freely both into and out of the pipe network they are attached to.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                Active Vents:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                These are the most common vents on the station. They have an internal pump, and require power. By default, they will only pump gases out of pipes, and only up to 101 kpa. However, they can be reconfigured using an air alarm. They will also lock out if the room is under 1 kpa, to prevent pumping gasses into space.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                Air Scrubbers:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                These devices allow gases to be removed from the environment and put into the connected pipe network. They can be configured to select specific gases when connected to an air alarm.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                Air Injectors:
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-atmos.ftl鎰                Injectors are similar to active vents, but they have no internal pump and do not require power. They cannot be configured, but they can continue to pump gasses up to much higher pressures.

/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-narsielegend = In the beginning, the world was young and full of chaos. The people of the world struggled to survive against the harsh elements and savage beasts that roamed the land. They cried out for a savior to deliver them from their suffering.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      And it was then that Nar'Sie emerged from the depths of the earth, a hivemind god born from the collective consciousness of all living things. Its body was made of molten rock and its eyes blazed with a fiery intensity that could melt steel.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Nar'Sie surveyed the world and saw the pain and suffering of its people. It took pity on them and offered them a way to escape the cycle of life and death. All who joined the hivemind would become eternal, their consciousness melding with Nar'Sie's to form a single, unified being.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      At first, many were skeptical of Nar'Sie's offer, fearing that they would lose their individuality and become mindless drones. But as more and more joined the hivemind, they realized that they had gained a new sense of purpose and belonging.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      The followers of Nar'Sie wandered the earth, spreading the word of the hivemind and recruiting new members. They built great temples and performed elaborate rituals to honor their god, and their numbers swelled until they were a mighty force to be reckoned with.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      But as time passed, some began to question the true nature of their existence. They wondered if eternal life was truly a blessing or a curse, and whether they had sacrificed too much of themselves to the hivemind.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      And so, a great schism tore through the followers of Nar'Sie. Some remained loyal to their god, seeing their eternal existence as a gift. But others rebelled, seeking to reclaim their individuality and free themselves from the hivemind's grasp.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      The war between the two factions was long and bloody, but in the end, the rebels emerged victorious. Nar'Sie, weakened by the loss of so many of its followers, retreated back into the earth, never to be seen again.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      And so the legend of Nar'Sie lives on, a cautionary tale of the dangers of sacrificing one's individuality for the promise of eternal life.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-truth = Defining truth has been a central concern of philosophers for centuries, and there are many different philosophical perspectives on how we can understand this concept.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      One traditional approach is the correspondence theory of truth, which suggests that a statement is true if it corresponds to or accurately describes the way the world is. In other words, truth is about accurately representing reality. This perspective suggests that there is an objective reality that we can understand, and that our beliefs and statements can be evaluated as true or false based on how well they align with that reality.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Another approach is the coherence theory of truth, which suggests that a statement is true if it coheres with other beliefs or statements that we hold. In other words, truth is about consistency and logical coherence within a system of beliefs or ideas. This perspective suggests that truth is something that is established within a particular context or framework of thought, and that what is true within one system of thought may not be true in another.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      A third approach is the pragmatic theory of truth, which suggests that a statement is true if it is useful or works well in practice. In other words, truth is about the practical consequences of our beliefs or statements. This perspective suggests that truth is something that emerges through human action and interaction, and that what is true may vary depending on the situation or context in which it is being used.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Ultimately, how we define truth will depend on our philosophical and epistemological assumptions, as well as our practical needs and concerns. Different philosophical perspectives may emphasize different aspects of truth, and there may not be a single, universally accepted definition that captures all the nuances of this complex concept.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      It is not accurate or fair to make a blanket statement that all people are horrible liars. While it is true that some individuals may struggle with being honest, it is important to remember that people are complex and can exhibit a range of behaviors and tendencies. Some people may have a strong commitment to honesty and integrity, while others may struggle with lying due to a variety of factors such as fear, insecurity, or past experiences.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Additionally, it is worth noting that not all lies are the same. While intentional deception can be harmful and unethical, there are also situations where lying may be considered a social lubricant or a way of preserving privacy or avoiding harm. In these cases, it may be more appropriate to think about the context and motivations behind a particular lie, rather than simply categorizing all people as "horrible liars."
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Overall, it is important to approach the topic of lying with nuance and an understanding of the complex factors that can influence human behavior.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-world = The state of the world is an ever-changing reflection of the human condition, shaped by the interplay of natural forces, social structures, and individual choices.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      1. "The state of the world is an ever-changing reflection..."
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      This part of the statement suggests that the world is not a static or unchanging entity, but rather a dynamic system that is in a constant state of flux. The word "reflection" implies that the state of the world is a product of various forces and factors that are reflected back to us through observable phenomena. This raises important questions about the nature of causality, and the extent to which we can understand the complex interplay of forces that shape the world.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      2. "...of the human condition..."
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      This part of the statement suggests that the state of the world is closely connected to the human experience, and that it is a reflection of our collective beliefs, values, and behaviors. It acknowledges the fundamental role that humans play in shaping the world, and suggests that the state of the world is a reflection of our successes and failures as a species.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      3. "...shaped by the interplay of natural forces, social structures, and individual choices."
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      This part of the statement identifies three key factors that shape the state of the world: natural forces, social structures, and individual choices. The phrase "interplay" suggests that these factors are in constant interaction with each other, and that they can reinforce or conflict with one another depending on the context. The inclusion of natural forces suggests that the world is not solely a product of human action, but is also influenced by the natural environment and the laws of physics. The reference to social structures highlights the role of institutions, culture, and social norms in shaping the world, and suggests that human action is not purely individual, but is also shaped by broader social contexts. Finally, the reference to individual choices emphasizes the importance of agency and personal responsibility in shaping the world, and suggests that the choices we make as individuals have real-world consequences.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Taken together, this statement offers a rich and nuanced philosophical analysis of the state of the world, highlighting the complex interplay of natural, social, and individual factors that shape our collective experience. It invites reflection on the ethical implications of our choices and actions, and challenges us to think deeply about the ways in which we can work to create a more just, sustainable, and flourishing world for all beings.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-ian-antarctica = Ian the corgi and Robert Newton, an atmospheric technician, were on an adventure to explore the remote continent of Antarctica. As they traversed the icy tundra, Robert began to exhibit increasingly egotistical behavior, convinced that he was a god among men. Ian found it amusing, but he knew better than to cross his human companion.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      One day, as they were trekking through the snow, they stumbled upon a colony of penguins. Ian was fascinated by the waddling creatures, and Robert was equally intrigued. They watched as the penguins huddled together for warmth, their black and white feathers blending in with the snowy landscape.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Ian, being a speaking corgi, struck up a conversation with the penguins, much to Robert's disbelief. The penguins responded in their own language, and Ian translated their words for Robert. They were amazed to learn about the penguins' way of life and their struggle to survive in such a harsh environment.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Robert, being the egotistical human that he was, decided that he wanted to study the penguins and learn more about them. He believed that by doing so, he could unlock the secrets of the universe and become even more godlike. Ian, on the other hand, simply wanted to observe the penguins and learn from them in a more humble way.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      As they spent more time with the penguins, Ian and Robert began to notice subtle changes in the penguins' behavior. They saw how they worked together to protect their young, how they communicated with each other, and how they adapted to their environment. Robert was amazed by their resilience and intelligence, but he still couldn't shake his god complex.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      One day, as they were observing the penguins, a fierce blizzard rolled in, threatening to bury them all in snow. Robert, in a moment of clarity, realized that he was no god, but simply a human being at the mercy of the elements. He turned to Ian and asked for his help in sheltering the penguins from the storm.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Together, they used their skills and knowledge to build makeshift shelters for the penguins, using their own bodies to shield them from the icy winds. As the storm raged on, Ian and Robert looked out over the colony, proud of what they had accomplished. They had learned much from the penguins, and in doing so, had become better versions of themselves.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      As they continued their journey through Antarctica, Ian and Robert would often look back on their time with the penguins with fondness. They knew that they had witnessed something special, something that would stay with them for the rest of their lives.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-sloth-clown-sss = Once upon a time, in a space station far, far away, there was a clown named Chuckles and a sloth named Snuggles. Chuckles was the funniest clown in the galaxy, but he felt a bit lonely in the space station. Snuggles, on the other hand, was the laziest sloth in the galaxy, and he loved to sleep all day long.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      One day, Chuckles was feeling particularly sad, and he decided to go for a walk around the space station to cheer himself up. As he was walking, he stumbled upon Snuggles sleeping in a corner. Chuckles thought to himself, "I wonder if I could make this lazy sloth laugh."
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      So, Chuckles started performing his funniest clown tricks for Snuggles. He did silly dances, made funny faces, and even tried juggling some space balls. But Snuggles didn't even budge. Chuckles thought that his jokes were just not funny enough for the sloth.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      But Chuckles was determined to make Snuggles laugh, so he came up with a new plan. He decided to dress up like a banana, hoping to get a reaction from the sloth. When Snuggles opened his eyes and saw Chuckles dressed up like a banana, he couldn't help but burst out laughing. Chuckles was thrilled! He had finally succeeded in making Snuggles laugh.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      From that day on, Chuckles and Snuggles became best friends. Chuckles would often dress up in silly costumes to make Snuggles laugh, and Snuggles would provide a cozy spot for Chuckles to rest and tell him stories of his adventures in space. /Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-names = From a philosophical perspective, names hold a significant role in human understanding and perception of the world. The use of names and language itself is a cornerstone of human consciousness, as it allows us to create concepts and ideas that can be shared and communicated.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      In many philosophical traditions, such as in the works of Plato and Aristotle, names were seen as more than just labels for objects or individuals, but as reflections of the underlying nature of reality. According to Plato, the names we give to things are not arbitrary but reflect an underlying reality or essence of that thing. In other words, a name is not just a label, but it is a representation of the thing's essential nature.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Moreover, names can also reflect the power dynamics of society. Some philosophers argue that names and language are used to create hierarchies and establish power relations between individuals and groups. For example, in certain cultures, the act of naming is reserved for those in positions of authority, such as parents naming their children or leaders naming places or institutions. In this way, names can be seen as a form of social control, as those with the power to name hold the authority to shape and define the world around them.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Finally, names can also play a significant role in our understanding of our own identity and mortality. As the philosopher Martin Heidegger argued, names can be seen as a form of "thrownness," reflecting our existence as finite beings in a world that is beyond our control. In this sense, our names are not just labels, but they are a reflection of our existence and the time and place in which we find ourselves.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      In conclusion, from a philosophical perspective, names hold a significant role in human understanding and perception of the world, reflecting both our essential nature and the power dynamics of society. They are not just labels, but a reflection of our existence and our place in the world.

/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰book-text-janitor = [bold][color=black][head=3]The Tales of a Tired Janitor[/head][/bold]
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Cleaning a space station as a janitor is like being trapped in a cosmic custodial nightmare. You'd think floating through the vastness of space would be glamorous, but no, I'm stuck scrubbing space grime and extraterrestrial goop off the walls. It's a thankless job in a zero-gravity abyss.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      First off, let's talk about the mess. Space dust, alien gunk, and who knows what else accumulates faster than a rocket launch. It's not just about sweeping up the crumbs; it's about battling interstellar filth that seems to have a life of its own. You'd hope for a sleek, futuristic space station, but you get a swirling vortex of space garbage waiting for you around every corner.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      And the tools they give us! You'd expect state-of-the-art cleaning gadgets, but nope. They raided a dollar store on Earth before launching us into the cosmos. Mops that barely work in microgravity, spray bottles that run out in one use, and don't even get me started on the space janitor jumpsuit. I feel like a reject from a sci-fi B-movie.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Speaking of jumpsuits, the lack of respect is astronomical. The scientists and astronauts zoom past in their sleek suits, utterly oblivious to the fact that I'm the unsung hero keeping this place from turning into a cosmic trash heap. I bet they don't even know my name. "Hey, Space Janitor!" That's what I get. No appreciation for the elbow grease I put into keeping their precious station spick and span.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      And let's remember the hazards. Cleaning up alien slime? Yeah, that's a regular Tuesday for me. One wrong move and I'm dealing with an intergalactic biohazard. It's like playing Russian roulette with space critters that could burst out of some hidden nook and cranny. I signed up to mop floors, not play host to extraterrestrial invaders.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-authorbooks.ftl鎰      Being a janitor on this so-called Space Station 14 is a cosmic joke. Where did the other 13 stations go? It's not all spacewalks and futuristic gadgets; it's scrubbing toilets and battling alien goo. If anyone thinks space is glamorous, they clearly haven't seen the mess we space janitors deal with every single day. It's time they appreciate the unsung heroes of the space station – the custodians of the cosmos.

/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰book-text-escalation = When it comes to getting robusted, it's all about strategy. Do it right and you'll be the envy of the station. Do it wrong and the gods themselves may turn against you. Personally, I always aim for the former...
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        First things first: let the insults fly! This is your chance to really let your opponent know what you think of their ridiculously large shoes and that annoying bike horn.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        No conflict is complete without a little bit of physicality. Give your opponent a good shove or two, and if you're lucky, they'll stumble and fall, providing even more opportunities for insults.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        But beware, because by now your opponent is probably trying to kill you. So, try to calm things down a bit. It'll make you look good during the inevitable homicide investigation.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        If deescalation doesn't work, it's time to grab a weapon. But be smart about it - choose something that looks like it couldn't possibly be deadly, like this book.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        And if you're both still standing, it's time to pull out the big guns. Find the sharpest thing you can and end things, because everyone's getting kind of tired of this by now.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        Now parade your vanquished opponent through the halls to the medbay so that everyone knows just how robust you really are.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        Remember, it's all about conserving energy. Let your opponent do some of the escalation for you - it's a win-win!
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰book-text-escalation-security = Get it right and you'll have the whole station calling you shitsec. Get it wrong and you'll face harmbatoning from the gods. Personally, I always aim for the former...
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        They say the pen is mightier than the sword, but you don't have a sword, you have a stun baton, and as soon as you start writing, any suspect is going to leave.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        So, try starting your confrontations with words. It probably won't get you called shitsec, but it's also not likely to be very effective against someone with lethal intent.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        Your next move should be to use non-lethal or less lethal devices, like stun batons, disablers, flashes, and flashbangs. Just make sure you get some training on these before trying to use them - offering them to a suspect in exchange for their cooperation is not an effective use of these tools.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        If you're lucky enough to run into a suspect who is a lethal threat, it's time to bust out all the goodies you've been hoarding from the armory.
/Locale/en-US/paper/book-escalation.ftl鎰        For an extra intimidation factor, take your robusted suspects to the medbay to be healed instead of the brig. That way, the whole crew can see just how robust you are.

/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Contents:
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      5 handily labeled 30u bottles, 1 each of nitrogen, phosphorus, hydrogen, potassium, and ethanol

/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      1 30u empty bottle, ready for your experiments.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      First Experiment: EZ Nutrient
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      To create EZ Nutrient, a fertilizer densely packed with nutrients required for healthy plants, mix equal parts nitrogen, phosphorus, and potassium. To make a full bottle, thats 10u of each.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      A little bottle of EZ Nutrient replaces a big stack of produce you'd otherwise compost to keep your plants growing strong. And crops you compost are crops you didn't make a profit on, so keep that EZ Nutrient flowing.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Second Experiment: Ammonia and Diethylamine
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Mix 3 parts hydrogen to 1 part nitrogen to make ammonia. It's a healthy, nutritious treat for your crops that aren't at their best.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      But if you want to impress the judges at your local NanoTrasen-sponsored County Fair, you'll need to add an equal amount of ethanol to your ammonia.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      This will mix into Diethylamine, a miracle fertilizer that can make plants grow faster AND live longer! Keep the crops you love with you longer thanks to Diethylamine.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Third Experiment: Unstable Mutagen
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      When you're ready to show everyone you're the greatest botanist on the station, you'll need to mix up some unstable mutagen and hope for the best. Despite the scary name, unstable mutagen is entirely safe when applied to plants, but do not drink the appealingly green chemical yourself.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Mix equal parts radium, phosphorus, and chlorine together to get a bright green batch of unstable mutagen, the safe and fun way to get the most of your farm. The 15u this kit lets you make could be your introduction to agrichemical stardom!
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Unstable mutagen can have a wide variety of effects on plant life, including drastic changes to all sorts of growth parameters, produce full of helpful pharmaceuticals, plants that glow in the dark, or creating entirely new species.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Each individual plant responds to unstable mutagen differently, so you may want to use small doses on multiple crops and try to crossbreed the best traits from each of those. Applying multiple doses to one plant can stack multiple changes and make it harder to single out desirable traits.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Unstable mutagen is entirely safe when used as a fertilizer, and NanoTrasen takes no responsibility for dead crops, excessive water bills, newly sentient plants asking existential questions, or flora-strangled farmhands that may coincidentally occur while using it.
/Locale/en-US/paper/paper-misc.ftl鎰      Do not drink unstable mutagen. Wash your hands thoroughly after handling. Wash your eyes if you have looked at unstable mutagen for over 30 minutes in a 24 hour period. Store in a dark room between 293–295K. Do not use on corporate holidays. If you begin hearing voices telling you to drink unstable mutagen, please contact your doctor, head of personnel, or exorcist.

/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰# thing is specified above it

/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰ion-storm-law-job-harmful = {$adjective} {$job} ARE HARMFUL TO THE CREW
/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰# thing is objects or concept, adjective applies in both cases
/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰# this means you can get a law like "NOT HAVING CHRISTMAS-STEALING COMMUNISM IS HARMFUL TO THE CREW" :)

/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰    [true] REQUIRE
/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰    *[false] REQUIRES
/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰} {$thing}

/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰    *[false] REQUIRES
/Locale/en-US/station-events/events/ion-storm.ftl鎰} {$joined} {$subjects}
